subSubSection.paragraph:
Material examined. Type material. Holotype
— NHMUK 1923.10.1.31, dry subsample from R.N.XXVII, 7 miles east of North Cape, 128 m , British Antarctica (
Terra Nova
) Expedition, 1910, 16 Jul– 24 Sep 1911; NHMUK 1926.5.1.114 & NHMUK 1923.10.1.231, microscope slides from R.N.XXVII, 7 miles east of North Cape, 128 m , British Antarctica (
Terra Nova
) Expedition, 1910, 16 Jul– 24 Sep 1911.

Skeleton.
Cortical skeleton thin (
100–200 µm
), poorly defined, consisting of an interwoven mesh of tangential microxeas and microrhabds that form a regular pattern around circular pores, 
150 µm
diameter (
Figure 1C
). Sub- dermal canals separate the cortex from the choanosome. Choanosomal skeleton has a single layer of dichotriaenes just below the cortex, cladomes uppermost (
Figure 1B
). Oxeas are more-or-less radially arranged near the surface but are confused towards the centre of the sponge (
Figure 1A
). Microxeas and tylasters are abundant and scattered throughout the choanosome, with tylasters more commonly found in the walls of the aquiferous canals.

Spicules
(
Figure 2
; 
Table 1
). 
Megascleres
—oxeas (
Figure 2A
) are small, fusiform and slightly curved; 1212 (978–1404) × 33 (22–45) µm (n = 20). Dichotriaenes (
Figure 2B & C
) are stout with a short conical rhabdome that strongly tapers to a sharp point. Rhabdome is similar in length to the width of the cladome. Occasionally, plagiotriaenes are found that are of similar size to dichotriaenes (
Figure 2D
), some of which may have the odd bifurcate clad tip (
Figure 2E
); 543 (390–637) µm long × 545 (401–652) µm wide (n = 20).

Microscleres
—microxeas (
Figure 2F
) are curved or sharply angulate towards the distal ends, often centrotylote, variable in size; 198 (85–287) × 14 (8–20) µm (n = 20). Microrhabds (
Figure 2G
) are small, smooth and curved with bluntly rounded tips, most are faintly centrotylote; 55 (36–79) × 6 (4–8) µm (n = 20). Tylasters (
Figure 2H
) are very small with numerous rays that have recurved spines at the tips; 9 (7–12) µm in diameter (n = 20).
